interactions.lmstext: 1. The skin is ________ to the bones.
2. The intestines are ________ to the esophagus.
3. The lumbar region of the back is ________ to the cervical region.
4. The head is ________ to the body.
5. The heart is ________ to the lungs.
6. The stomach is ________ to the heart.
7. The elbow is ________ to the hand.
8. The breast bone is ________ to the vertebral column.
9. The spleen is an unpaired, left-sided structure. It is possible to see the spleen in all of the following planes of section, EXCEPT:
10. The kidneys are bilaterally paired structures not found in the midline. In which plane of section is it possible to see only one kidney?
11. Choose one INCORRECT statement regarding a human in the anatomical position.

choices.lmstext: The lungs are lateral to the heart.
The palms are on the ventral surface of the hands.
The wrist is distal to the elbow.
The skin is superficial to the viscera.
The thorax is inferior to the pelvis.

interactions.lmstext: 12. Which of the following planes divides the body into two symmetrical right / left halves?
13. What movement is occurring in the knee?
14. What movement is occurring in the spine?
15. What movement is occurring in the spine?
16. What movement is occurring in the wrist?
17. What movement is occurring in the shoulder?
18. What movement is occurring in the fingers?
19. What movement is occurring in the knuckles?
20. What movement is occurring in the shoulder?
1. What is the target of somatic motor fibres?
2. Which of the following functional subtypes of neurons is found in the dorsal ramus? Choose all that apply.

choices.lmstext: sensory from the body wall and limbs

interactions.lmstext: 3. What is the difference between a dorsal ramus and a ventral ramus?

choices.lmstext: Dorsal rami contain sensory fibres only and ventral rami contain motor fibres only.
They innervate different classes of target tissues in the same region of the body.
They innervate the same classes of target tissues, but in different regions of the body.
There is no difference; the terms are synonymous

interactions.lmstext: 4. Identify the INCORRECT statement regarding the subdivisions of the nervous system.

choices.lmstext: Somatic motor fibres innervate cardiac muscle.
Sympathetic output arises from spinal levels T1 - L2.
The autonomic nervous system provides sensory input from organs.
The parasympathetic nervous system dominates during rest and the sympathetic system dominates in times of stress.

interactions.lmstext: 5. Which of the following classes of neurons are pseudounipolar?

choices.lmstext: sensory from the body wall and limbs

interactions.lmstext: 6. A dermatome is formed by contributions from both the dorsal ramus and the ventral ramus that arise from a given spinal nerve.
7. Which of the following functional subtypes of neurons is found in a ventral root arising from the spinal cord in the cervical region? Choose all that apply.
8. Which of the following functional subtypes of neurons is found in a ventral root arising from the spinal cord in the lower lumbar region? Choose all that apply.
9. Which of the following functional subtypes of neurons is found in a dorsal root? Choose all that apply.

choices.lmstext: sensory from the body wall and limbs

interactions.lmstext: 10. What are the defining characteristics of dorsal root ganglia? Choose all that apply.

choices.lmstext: they are a component of the peripheral nervous system
they are a component of the central nervous system

interactions.lmstext: 11. Which of the following are mixed (both sensory and motor) nerves? Choose all that apply.
12. Dorsal rami are typically larger than ventral rami.
13. What are the targets of the sympathetic nervous system in the body wall and limbs? Choose all that apply.

choices.lmstext: muscle in the walls of blood vessels
smooth muscle that makes your hair stand on end

interactions.lmstext: 14. What nerves deliver sensory fibres to the skin overlying the vertebral column?
15. What nerves deliver voluntary motor fibres to the muscle adjacent to the spine?
16. Ventral rami are larger than dorsal rami.
17. A patient presents with skin that is red and dry. What functional component of their peripheral nerves is not functional?
1. Identify the CORRECT statement regarding the cervical vertebrae.

choices.lmstext: They have the largest vertebral body.
They have costal facets on their transverse processes.
Their spinous processes are blunt, square and extend straight backwards from the neural arch.
Their zygopophysial joints are sloped from anterior to posterior.

interactions.lmstext: 2. What passes through the foramen indicated by the arrow?
3. Identify the INCORRECT statement regarding the ligaments of the vertebral column.

choices.lmstext: Because of the location of the anterior and posterior longitudinal ligaments, herniated discs will more commonly protrude out laterally.
The ligamenta flava have a lower elastic fibre content than most other ligaments, and therefore greatly restrict flexion of the vertebral column.
The interspinous and supraspinous ligaments act to restrict flexion of the vertebral column.
The transverse ligament holds the dens in place, allowing the atlas to rotate around the dens.

interactions.lmstext: 4. Identify the sacral promontory (click the image).
5. Identify the CORRECT statement regarding the vertebral column.

choices.lmstext: The laminae connect the pedicles to the vertrbral body.
The C7 spinous process is not palpatable.
During development, the dens of the axis begins as the vertebral body of the atlas.
The orientation of the zygopophyseal joints is the same between different regions of the spinal column.

interactions.lmstext: 1. Identify the INCORRECT statement regarding the spinal cord and nerves.

choices.lmstext: Below the cervical level, spinal nerves are numbered according to the vertebral body above their point of exit.
The spinal cord ends as the conus medullaris at approximately the L2 vertebral body.
The dorsal and ventral rootlets decrease in length from rostral to caudal.
Spinal nerves exit through the intervertebral foramina.

interactions.lmstext: 2. You are looking into the lumbar cistern. Which layer of the meninges contributes to the structure indicated by the arrow?
3. Identify the CORRECT statement regarding the meninges.

choices.lmstext: The filum terminale externa is an extension of pia mater from the conus medularis within the lumbar cistern.
In life, the space between the dura and arachnoid mater is filled with cerebral spinal fluid (CSF).
The dura and arachnoid mater form the dural sac.
The dural sac begins at the L2 vertebral body and ends at the S2 vertebral body.

interactions.lmstext: 4. Click on the star that corresponds to the level at which a lumbar puncture is typically performed.
5. This is a posterior view of a spinal cord in situ. Identify the structures indicated by the arrow.
1. A nerve contains only somatic motor fibres and sympathetic preganglionic fibres. What nerve is it?
2. A nerve contains only sensory fibres, bringing information into the spinal cord from the body surface and from internal organs. What nerve is it?
3. A ganglion contains pseudounipolar cell bodies. Which ganglion is it? Choose all that apply.
4. A nerve contains sensory fibres, somatic motor fibres and sympathetic postganglionic fibres. What nerve might it be? Choose all that apply.
5. How do dorsal and ventral rami differ? Choose all that apply.

choices.lmstext: dorsal and ventral rami innervate different regions of the body
dorsal rami are smaller than ventral rami
the axons in dorsal and ventral rami target different tissue types
dorsal and ventral rami contain different functional groups of axons

interactions.lmstext: 6. A nerve contains sympathetic preganglionic fibres. What nerve might it be? Choose all that apply.
7. A nerve contains sympathetic postganglionic fibres. What nerve might it be? Choose all that apply.
8. A ventral root contains somatic motor fibres, but no sympathetic preganglionic fibres. At what level of the spinal cord is this ventral root located? Choose all that apply.

choices.lmstext: a ventral root at any cervical level
a ventral root between T1 and L2

interactions.lmstext: 9. Which spinal nerves are connected to the sympathetic chain by both a white ramus communicans and a grey ramus communicans? Choose all that apply.

choices.lmstext: a ventral root between T1 and L2
a ventral root at any cervical level

interactions.lmstext: 10. Which spinal nerves are connected to the sympathetic chain by a grey ramus communicans, but not a white ramus communicans? Choose all that apply.

choices.lmstext: a ventral root at any cervical level
a ventral root between T1 and L2

interactions.lmstext: 1. Which spinal levels contribute to the formation of the brachial plexus? Choose all that apply.
2. Which spinal levels contribute to the formation of the dorsal scapular nerve (as indicated by the arrow)? Choose all that apply.
3. Which spinal levels contribute to the formation of the long thoracic nerve (as indicated by the arrow)? Choose all that apply.
4. Which spinal levels contribute to the formation of the lateral cord of the brachial plexus (as indicated by the arrow)?
5. Which spinal levels contribute to the formation of the radial nerve (as indicated by the arrow)?
6. Which dermatomes (spinal levels) contribute to the sensory distribution of the ulnar nerve (as indicated by the arrow)?
7. Which spinal levels contribute to the formation of the medial cord of the brachial plexus (as indicated by the arrow)?
